<TITLE> Stocks rise after 3-day downturn </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Sept 19 (bdnews24.com) - Stocks ended up Wednesday, buoyed by renewed buying after a three-day downturn. "It's a rational response," said Yawer Sayeed, who helps manage about Tk 800 million in funds at AIMS of Bangladesh. He said new buying was being seen after the market passed a correction phase. "The market has found a new support level at 2500 and a resistance level at 2600 points. So in the short run, market movement should be between 2500-2600 points," he said. The market rose in the first half of trading and fell slightly in the second session, before closing up. Power stocks moved up with the exception of Power Grid Company of Bangladesh. Summit Power led the upbeat. The banking sector finished mixed but stocks with low market capitalisation gained. The DGEN or general index added 4.98 points or 0.19 percent to 2514.61. The DSI or all-share price gained 7.11 points or 0.34 percent to 2080.17. The DSE-20 blue chip finished at 1998.56, up 3.61 points or 0.18 percent from the previous day. Gainers ruled losers 101 to 81. Some 22 scrips held steady. A total of 15,158,562 shares worth Tk 1.27 billion traded. The Chittagong Stock Exchange ended upbeat with 49 issues gained, 37 lost and 10 ended unchanged. Turnover on the bourse stood at Tk 165.30 million from transaction of 2,493,840 shares. Summit Power, the leader in turnover, rallied 5.69 percent to Tk 1460.75. DESCO rose 1.24 percent to Tk 1157. BRAC Bank, second most traded issue, slipped 0.54 percent to Tk 1234.25. Grameen1 mutual fund grew 5.74 percent to an all-time high of Tk 57.10 after it reported a 29 percent cash dividend for the year 2006-07. AIMS 1st MF also climbed 6.88 percent to close at an all time high of Tk 6.52, after recording a steady growth in net asset value in recent months. Bangladesh Finance, Mercantile Insurance and Olympic were top gainers. Popular Life Insurance, 6th ICB MF and Tallu Spinning were major losers. 
